Reviving the very American ideal that labor rights are also human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed legislation to protect union organizing as a civil right.
&quot;The way unions work, middle-class jobs work,&quot; says Ellison, the Democratic senator from Minnesota who co-chairs the congressional committee.
That&#39;s why I&#39;m so proud to co-introduce the Workers&#39; Empowerment Act with occasional rights paragon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to defend against union organizing discrimination as other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces
Amending the Labor Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination if they want to join a union to sue in civil court - and be awarded compensation or damages - is a right and necessary initiative.
But it&#39;s certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and other proponents are proposing in the bill is to revisit the American ideal.
Despite the union battles that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states - Americans once encouraged countries around the world to adopt, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember it, when the country championed democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of assembly in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers encouraged the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toja&#39;s military autocracy would be replaced by democracy.
Convinced that workers and their unions had a role to play in shaping the new Japan, they included language and openly recognized that &quot;the right of workers to assemble, bargain collectively, and act is guaranteed.&quot;
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers encouraged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler&#39;s fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to organize and assert themselves in the new nation, the Germans included a clause that bluntly stated: &quot;The right to form associations to secure and improve labor and economic conditions shall be guaranteed to every individual and every occupation or profession.&quot;
Arrangements that limit this right or seek to impair it will be void. Measures leading to the fulfillment of such a purpose are illegal.
When former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights that drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations as a global treaty in 1948, the drafters and Roosevelt included the guarantee that &quot;everyone has the right to the protection of his interests form and join unions.&#39;
Americans for generations have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries how to create a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to form labor unions - and to participate in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are under attack in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and assert themselves in a free and open society.
As the Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Everyone knows today that trade unions have not diminished the power of the nation, but have expanded it.
They raised the standard of living of millions of people, created a market for industry and raised production to unimagined levels.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History doesn&#39;t forget and neither should we.
Formal recognition of labor rights as human - and the extension of civil rights protections to prevent discrimination in union organizing - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis restore the ideals that raised America and made it the true promise of democracy.
A judge has temporarily blocked a law that could have closed all abortion clinics in Louisiana
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked a Louisiana law that advocates say would have likely shut down all five abortion clinics in the state.
