&quot;Today&#39;s decision ensures Louisiana women will be safe from an insidious law designed to rob them of their health and rights,&quot; said Nancy Northup, president and CEO of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which sued on behalf of three of the five clinics seeking the block. of the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applies to doctors from the two clinics who were not among the plaintiffs and are also seeking that permission.
Louisiana is among eleven states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional by provision.
A federal judge on Friday blocked key parts of a Texas law that would have shut down most of the remaining clinics in the state.
Abortion advocates, along with the Association of American Obstetricians and Gynecologists and the American Medical Association, argue that the requirement to have this license places medically unnecessary requirements on doctors.
Opponents of abortion countered that the measures were intended to protect women&#39;s health, and some also welcomed the fact that the measures would close clinics.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one doctor is licensed to perform abortions in Louisiana.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure out of fear for his safety, the group said.
In response, Louisiana authorities said they would not penalize doctors who perform abortions while waiting for a license application to be processed.
