Most cancers are difficult to determine what caused them.
Although some smokers get lung cancer, not all lung cancer patients have smoked.
But mesothelioma is different.
In almost all cases, the cause is exposure to asbestos - a fibrous building material that was once called a &quot;miracle&quot; but is now known to be deadly.
For most of us, mesothelioma was not difficult to ignore.
Asbestos, after all, is a thing of the past.
The most dangerous type of asbestos has not been used in Britain since the 1960s, when a ban on the use of asbestos in industry came into effect.
Even at the time when asbestos was used, only certain groups of people came into close contact with it, such as insulation layers, builders, carpenters and shipyard workers.
A toxin used in industry in another era hardly seems a cause for concern today.
But such complacency is out of place.
As it turns out, the mesothelioma epidemic is at its peak in Britain today.
The number of deaths from mesothelioma is higher here than in any other country in the world.
The 2,500 deaths per year from this disease are twice the number of car accident victims.
