The reason we are only now feeling its effects, even though the use of asbestos has been illegal for years (all types of asbestos were finally banned by law in 1999), is that mesothelioma usually takes several decades to develop.
The scourge of mesothelioma does not only affect veterans of the construction industry.
Asbestos was, and in many cases still is, present in the homes we live in, the offices we work in, the schools we learn in, and the stores we shop in.
Thus, mesothelioma does not respect social class, wealth, occupation or age.
Privileged bastions from London department stores to public schools are no shelter.
Even Parliament is full of asbestos.
Even the hospitals where they are supposed to treat us are repositories of this deadly carcinogen.
