A verbal agreement with an employer can be a problem
Unfortunately, you did not have a certificate of incapacity for work issued by a doctor, which serves as proof for the organization that you are unable to perform work duties for health reasons.
In addition, you did not immediately notify your employer of your absence.
Subsequently, an agreement was reached that the given days would be registered as a holiday, but the agreement was only made verbally.
Although the Labor Code does not impose an obligation to have the employer&#39;s consent to taking leave confirmed in writing, this procedure has proven itself in practice.
If there is only a verbal agreement, you do not have confirmation of the agreement.
Later, as in your case, the alleged consent to taking leave may be denied and the absence from work considered a long-term unexcused absence, thus a reason for the immediate termination of the employment relationship according to § 53 of the Labor Code.
In the event of a lawsuit about the agreement with the employer, you lack provable evidence.
However, the employment relationship with you was not canceled according to § 53, you only have the given days listed in the credit card as an unexcused absence.
An unexcused absence in the credit card does not have the same consequences as § 53 (e.g. the impossibility of receiving unemployment benefits), but it does make it more difficult to find a new job.
We recommend that you visit the doctor in question again and get a written confirmation that there really was an injury, as a result of which you were unable to work (this is not a so-called &quot;incapacity&quot;, it is only a doctor&#39;s certificate).
When looking for a new job, you can present the aforementioned document and explain the situation.
In practice, it is advisable not to underestimate both the issuance of a written medical certificate of incapacity for work, as well as early notification to the employer or the request for written consent to taking leave.
This way you avoid possible complications.
