Why can the universe have multiple dimensions and we can&#39;t see them?
Physicists don&#39;t usually write bestsellers, but in 1999 Brian Greene of Columbia University managed to hit the nail on the head.
His book The Elegant Universe has become the most accessible way for the layman to penetrate the thicket of problems that many theoretical physicists are dealing with today - the attempt to unify two brilliantly functioning but mutually incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and general relativity.
Undoubtedly, one of the reasons for the success of The Elegant Universe is that in the case of the search for a unified theory of physics, it is not a boring story.
Physicists have solved the basic problem between two key theories (because at this moment our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) and are solving it so imaginatively that it is worth retelling even to laymen.
In addition, Greene handled the complex material in such a fresh and engaging manner that he cannot be blamed for not including much of the interesting in his book.
Moreover, he mostly corrected his &quot;mistake&quot; in two other books: Structure of the Universe and Hidden Reality.
The author probably wouldn&#39;t object to his book becoming obsolete more quickly, but the fact is that even after 15 years, The Elegant Universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with an ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It is quite likely that in the coming years there will be a bit more activity in this field (perhaps because the LHC accelerator will finally go &quot;full throttle&quot;), so it is a good time to enter the door of the world of modern physics that Green has gently opened.
How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe might have more than three spatial dimensions may certainly sound silly, fantastical, strange, or mystical.
Nevertheless, it is specific and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let&#39;s turn our gaze for a moment from the universe as a whole to something more mundane, namely a long and thin garden hose.
Imagine stretching a 100-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watching the entire scenery from half a kilometer away (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily see a long hose stretched horizontally, but unless you are very clairvoyant, you can hardly make out the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you&#39;d think that an ant forced to live on a hose would only have one dimension to walk in: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at a given moment, you answer with just one piece of information: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we mean by all this is that from half a kilometer away, a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, hose has thickness.
If we enlarge everything, we suddenly see the second dimension - in the shape of a circle wrapping the hose.
In this magnified view, it is clear that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the &quot;clockwise/counter-clockwise dimension&quot;, i.e. around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of the little ant you need to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where it is on the circle that wraps around the hose.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note. Experts will note that this chapter focuses purely on perturbation string theory.
Non-disruptive aspects are discussed in Chapters 12 and 13.).
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the circumferential dimension, indicated by a circular arrow, is short and coiled.
However, there is a clear difference between the two dimensions.
The dimension along the hose is long and easy to see.
The dimension wrapping the circumference of the hose is short, &quot;rolled&quot; and less noticeable.
In order to realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
The mentioned example illustrates an important property of spatial dimensions.
The fact that they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, extensive and therefore directly visible, or, on the contrary, small, rolled up and much more difficult to observe.
Of course, in the mentioned case, we didn&#39;t exactly go out of our way to reveal the &quot;rolled&quot; dimension wrapping the thickness of the hose.
It was enough to take a telescope to help.
But if the hose were thinner - like a hair or a capillary - we would only reveal the coiled dimension with great effort.
Kaluza sent his paper to Einstein in 1919, in which he presented the astonishing idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than the three dimensions we all know.
Kaluza justified his radical claim by saying that the additional dimension provides an elegant and compelling framework in which Einstein&#39;s general relativity and Maxwell&#39;s electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptual structure.
The question immediately arises as to how this Kaluz observation goes together with the obvious fact that we see precisely three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein clearly stated and specified in 1926, rests on the proposition that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and convoluted dimensions.
This means that, just like the dimensions along the length of the hose, our universe has a large, vast and easily visible three dimensions, the existence of which we are aware of at every moment.
But analogous to the circular circumference of a garden hose, the universe may also have additional dimensions, tightly coiled into a space so tiny that they have so far remained hidden even from our most sophisticated experimental apparatus.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluz&#39;s remarkable proposal, let&#39;s stay with the hose for a moment.
Imagine that we draw a relatively dense series of circles on the circumference of the hose with black paint.
From a distance, the hose still looks like a thin one-dimensional line.
With the telescope, thanks to the drawing, we can now reveal the coiled dimension even more easily, because we will see the motif from Figure 2.
We can clearly see that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional, with one dimension large and almost unlimited and the other short and circular.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that our universe has a similar structure, but in addition to one small circular dimension, it has three large spatial dimensions, a total of four spatial dimensions.
It is difficult to draw an object with too many dimensions.
To give our imagination a little help, let&#39;s notice the illustration in Fig.3; shows two large dimensions and one small circular dimension.
In the picture, we enlarge the view of the geometry of the space in the same way as we enlarged the surface of the hose.
Each subsequent level represents a huge increase in the geometry of the space from the previous level.
Our universe can have additional dimensions (we see them at the fourth level of magnification) if they are rolled into a small enough space; this is how we explain that we have not yet directly observed them.
The square grid represents the commonly known &quot;large&quot; dimensions, while the circle represents the new, tiny, coiled dimension.
Just like the loops of thread in a densely woven carpet, these circles exist in every place of the usual dimensions - only for the sake of clarity we have drawn them only at the intersections of the square grid.
The background of figure 4 shows the commonly known structure of space - the ordinary world around us - at such common scales as meters, represented by the side of a small square in a square grid.
In each subsequent image, we focus on a small area of the previous image; we will enlarge it so that it becomes visible.
At first, nothing special happens, as we see in the first few zoom levels.
However, when we go further in our journey of the microscopic properties of the geometry of space - to the fourth level of magnification in Figure 3 - we suddenly see a new dimension coiled into a circle, similar to the loops of thread in a densely woven piece of carpet.
Kaluza and Klein came up with the idea that an additional circular dimension exists at every point in the direction of the large dimensions, just as a hose has a circular circumference at every point along its length.
For the sake of clarity, we have drawn the circular dimension only in some regularly spaced points.
Figure 4 summarizes Kaluz and Klein&#39;s idea of the microscopic structure of the geometry of space.
The similarity with the hose is obvious, although we also note important differences.
First, the universe has three large, far-reaching spatial dimensions (of which we have drawn only two), whereas the hose has only one large dimension.
An even more important difference is that we are now talking about the spatial geometry of the universe itself, not just some object inside the universe, like our hose.
But the basic idea is the same.
If the additional circular coiled dimension is extremely miniature, it is - like the circular circumference of the hose - much more difficult to recognize than to observe the obvious, large and vast dimensions.
If the size of the additional dimension is small enough, it will actually reveal it beyond the power of our state-of-the-art magnification tools.
But most importantly, the extra dimension is not just a round bump inside the regular dimensions, as the two-dimensional illustration mistakenly suggests.
The circular dimension is a new dimension that exists at every point of the three common vast dimensions.
It is a dimension independent of the other three dimensions, just as the top-down, left-right and front-back dimensions are independent (and perpendicular) to each other.
A sufficiently small ant could move in all four dimensions, and to determine its position we would need four data, in addition to the usual three, the position in the circular dimension; if we also count the time, then five figures, in any case one more than we would normally expect.
