The price for the e-book is CZK 149.
So, to our surprise, we find that even though we are aware of the existence of only three dimensions of space, Kaluz and Klein&#39;s reasoning shows that this does not exclude the existence of additional coiled dimensions, if they are small enough.
The universe may well have more dimensions than we can see with the naked eye.
How small should they be?
State-of-the-art technical equipment can recognize structures as large as a billionth of a billionth of a meter.
We can barely observe the smaller coiled dimensions.
In 1926, Klein combined Kaluz&#39;s original idea with several ideas from the nascent quantum mechanics.
His calculations suggested that the additional circular dimension could be about one Planck length in size, a size far beyond the resolving power of today&#39;s instruments.
Since then, physicists have called the possibility of additional tiny spatial dimensions the Kaluz-Klein theory.
