Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A woman from Britain describes how she thought she was going to die for many years after being misdiagnosed.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her teenage years believing she only had a few years left to live.
It was actually Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT) - a group of inherited disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The charity CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because so little is known about the disease.
Around 23,000 people in the UK are thought to suffer from CMT, which can present with motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, clumsy walking and twisted toes.
Those affected may also experience numbness or pain, the condition is incurable and progressive, meaning that symptoms worsen over time.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she had Freidreich&#39;s Ataxia (FA), a condition with a very poor prognosis.
She believed she would be wheelchair-bound before her eighteenth birthday and dead by the time she turned thirty.
The mother of two, now 51, says: “As a child I knew I couldn&#39;t do the same things as others.
Every day I fell and everything took longer.
I could never roller skate or skateboard with the other kids, and I was bullied at school because of the way I walked and ran.&#39;
When Rodgers was thirteen and coming off several surgeries to release her Achilles tendons and straighten her feet, she took advantage of her doctor leaving the room to consult her records, where she learned she had FA.
&quot;I felt guilty because I was snooping so I didn&#39;t tell anyone, but when I got home I looked up information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA,&quot; she says.
When they answered me, I was shocked, I completely panicked.
I thought that by the time I was eighteen, I would be in a wheelchair, and by the time I was twenty-five, I would be dead, and in the meantime I would gradually lose all my faculties.
I was all alone and I was planning my funeral.&#39;
When she was seventeen, she realized that her ability to walk had not deteriorated as much as she had assumed and asked her surgeon about it.
He just stood up and hugged her and said, “Sweetheart, I don&#39;t think you have the disease, or you&#39;d be in a wheelchair by now.
I think it will be something much less life-threatening.&#39;
After undergoing several genetic tests, he was diagnosed with CMT.
“When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was lucky,” she said.
The CMT UK charity has launched CMT Awareness Month to raise awareness of the disease.
Washington area entrepreneurs: taxes rise as economy turns around
A growing economy means more customers, more sales and more jobs.
And higher taxes too.
According to a new survey released last week, state and local business taxes across the country rose slightly last year as the economy accelerated, and Washington businesses were no exception.
Businesses in Maryland and Virginia contributed a combined $27.6 billion to state and local coffers in fiscal year 2013, a 3.8% increase over the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden - both state and local - rose 4.3% to $671 billion last year, compared with 3.9% the previous year, marking the third consecutive year of growth after 2009 and 2010, when taxes were cut.
According to the study, by professional firm Ernst &amp; Young and the Center on State Taxation, a political group, state taxes rose faster, at 4.3%, than local levies, at 3.9%.
More than half of the district&#39;s tax revenue, 56%, is from the business tax, and 36% of Maryland&#39;s revenue is from corporations.
Virginia, at 28%, has proportionally the least business tax revenue.
Researchers say the majority of tax revenue growth came from increases in the value of business-owned properties, which increased property taxes by 3.7% this year after three consecutive years of -1% growth.
Although most of the profit comes from big states like California, New York and Texas, it seems the situation is the same in Washington.
Companies in DC, Maryland and Virginia paid over $10 billion in state and local property taxes last year, a 4.2% year-over-year increase from $9.6 billion in 2012.
But the apparent increase in property values doesn&#39;t drive up state and local tax revenue as much in Maryland, where property taxes account for less than a fifth of corporate taxation.
For businesses in Virginia and DC, property taxes account for nearly half of state and local taxation.
&quot;A lot of real estate in Maryland is owned by businesses, primarily the tax base around DC, by government or non-profit organizations that don&#39;t pay taxes,&quot; explained Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the Center on State Taxation.
So Maryland is forced to rely much more on income taxes, for example, to pay for the same services that are in other states.
The recent increase in business tax revenue cannot be attributed solely to the recovering real estate market.
According to the data, business income also appears to be increasing.
Businesses in the region posted $2.3 billion in corporate income tax, up from $2.1 billion in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion in corporate income taxes, the most in the region.
Although they are moving in the same direction, the local tax burden on entrepreneurs is not growing at the same rate in these three places.
DC&#39;s growth rate was in line with the national average, at 4.3%, while Maryland&#39;s growth was significantly higher at 4.9%.
Only in Virginia was the tax increase below average, at 4.1%.
Virginia has the lowest corporate income tax of the three districts (all of which are taxed the same), at 6%.
Maryland&#39;s corporate tax rate is 8.25%, while the DC average remains relatively high at 9.975%.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce this year found that Virginia has lower state and local taxes and an overall more favorable tax climate than Maryland.
DC did not evaluate the study.
Despite this advantage, Virginia faces pressure from competition from the south.
North Carolina recently signed into law cutting the corporate tax from 6.9% to 6%, as did Virginia, and the tax will drop to 5% next year.
If the state continues to meet revenue targets in the coming year, the statutory income tax rate could drop to as low as 3% in 2017.
According to a recent study, small business owners in Washington are doing better and therefore paying higher state and local taxes.
The business tax levied by small business owners as a personal income tax — the structure to offset cost increases by raising prices by which most businesses are organized — rose 20% to $2.4 billion in D.C., Maryland and Virginia last year, much faster than other taxes.
Researchers say the trend and statewide business tax increases are likely to continue next year, with total sales tax revenue for state and local governments rising 6.2% in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
But Washington may be lagging behind as government spending cuts take a toll on the labor market.
