The second fundamental lie of creationism is the belief that the sacred texts were written by god and not by actual human authors.
When believers debate one of the many things that conflict with their religion, we are often faced with the question: Whom will you believe?
The alleged word of God, or the word of man?
As if human investigation were nothing compared to the authority they imagine their doctrine has.
But when they say &quot;man&quot;, they are talking about science.
And when they refer to the &quot;word of God&quot;, they refer to myths about God written down by humans.
If there really is an intelligent creator with a purpose, then he is the one who created the fossil record that reveals evolutionary history, and he must be the one who devised the genetic patterns that correspond to it, and he must be the one who supplied the other lines evidence that points exclusively to the evolutionary conclusion down to the last detail.
Why else would all these things exist?
It seems like he&#39;s trying to tell us something!
Humans could not create any of those things.
But people know how to tell stories, to tell stories.
And it was men who wrote all those texts that pretend to be the word of God.
Every supposedly holy teaching of any religion in the world describes itself as written by men, not gods.
By people who were &quot;moved&quot; or &quot;inspired&quot; by their favorite gods, or perhaps listened to the dictates of angels, but those texts were written by none other than mere mortals with some degree of imagination, not angels and certainly not gods.
If there really was one true god, he would be an integral part of all the gods of all religions, an über-galactic supergenius, the ultimate entity of the entire cosmos.
If a being of such magnitude ever wrote a book, there would be only one such book, one holy scripture.
It would be known everywhere in the world, without predecessors, parallels or alternatives in any language, because mere human authors could not measure up to such a work.
And people would not have to blindly believe it, because it would be consistent, supported by verifiable and true evidence, and would reveal a deep morality and wisdom far beyond all human limits.
It would permanently inspire every reader to the unity of the common faith.
If god had written it, we would expect nothing less.
But what we see instead is the exact opposite.
Instead of a single religion leading to the ultimate truth, we have many different religions with no common origin, all continually breaking up into more and more separate denominations, seeking disputed truths, each claiming divine guidance in some way, regardless of continued divergence and separation in every direction.
The Jewish Torah, the Christian Gospels, the Islamic Koran, Bahá&#39;u&#39;lláh&#39;s Kitáb-i-Aqdás, Zarathustra&#39;s Avesta, the Sikh Adí-Granth, the Mahabharata Bhagavad-Gita, the Book of Mormon, or the Urantia Book are all considered &quot;absolute truth&quot; and &quot;revealed the word of the one true god&quot; and the respective believers of each say that the others are misguided.
The only logical explanation is probably that everyone is misguided to some degree.
None of the books mentioned above have any advantage over the others.
None of them are supported by evidence and none can be historically confirmed.
My name is Dr. Paul Maier, and I&#39;m a professor of ancient history at Western Michigan University.
I am not saying that I have proven the Bible to be reliable and historically accurate.
Of course it isn&#39;t.
You still have to have faith.
